{"/service/ndnp/sdhi/batch_sdhi_guava_ver02/data/sn85042792/00332899946/1921021001/0155.xml":{"full_text":"PAGE FOUR\nThe Brookings Register\nPublished Every Thursday By\nREGISTER PUBLISHING COMPANY\nBROOKINGS. SOUTH DAKOTA\nI\u2019aul Dutcher, Publisher and Proprietor\nOfliclnl City and County P\u00bbtw*r\nForeign Advertising Representative\n_THE AMERICAN PRESS ASSOCIATION J\nliliircHH nil Communication* to Register\nPublishing Company.\nst l.S< RJPTIOS PRICE\nOne Year\nHix Month-\nThree Month* 100\nSubscription sirictly In Advance\nEntered al the l<>-lolfice in Brookings ua\nIh-eond la-s Mall .Matter.\nir< illation, 1,000; ail paid in advance.\niMsplav advertising rates, 30 cents per inch.\nKeadiiig notices, cent* per line. Paid\nhn .il*>. cents per litie. All iegals governed\nIn Stair law. la-hilled columns, one cent\na Horn with minimum al cents per in\nsertion.\nPaul Dutcher Managing Editor\nj, Irot/.ig Issociule ami News\nTHE WRONG REMEDY\nA lively fight Ims been siarb-d at\nthe state capital o\\< r a bill to remove\nthe state university from Vermillion\nto Sioux Falls, under the guise of\ngreater growth of that institution\nthrough greater town backing ami\ngreater opportunities such as a large\ncity like Sioux Falls would have to\noffer. The proposal attracts great in\nterest in Brookings through the kin\ndred relationship of State college to\nthe university. But it especially in\nterests the citizens of Brookings after\nreading the following editorial from\nthe Huronite:\n\u201cThe state\u2019s two largest educational\ninstitutions are located m towns whose\npossible support of them Is limited,\nand both these schools are under\nmore or less of a handicap on that\naccount. The state university is one\nand the state college is the other.\nThe state college should be at Huron,\nand this is a fact that is admitted by\nmembers of the corps in charge of tiie\nsplendid work being done at Brook\nings. There is a limit to what a small\ntown can do for a great institution,\nwhereas no limit ought to be put on\nthe development of any state s educa\ntional institutions. Even if it must\nbe at material sacrifice, the education\nof the coming generations of South\nDakotans in South Dakota should not\nbe held back.\u2019\u2019\nThe contentions of both Sioux Falls\nand Huron are based on the entirely\nerroneous impression that the success\nand grow th of a state institution de\npends upon the town in which it is\nlocated. The town does not make the\nschool. The growth of the school\ndepends upon the state for it is a\nstate institution. If the state builds\nup the school the school will grow.\nThe state should have greater pride\nin their educational institutions than\nto allow them to depend upon any one j\ntown for their support. The only\nhandicap of the state institutions in\nthis state is meager appropriations for\ntheir development and growth, and not\nbecause they happen to be situated in\nsmall cities. We fall to note where\nthe universities and state colleges of\nMichigan, California, Washington, Ore- I\ngon, lowa, Missouri, Nebraska, Colo\nrado, Illinois, and hundreds of others\nof the greatest and largest schools in\nthe United States suffer any handicap\nby being located in small towns.\nWithout exception these schools con\nsider it an advantage to be located in\na small town. Pennsylvania State col\nlege was located in no town w\u2019hatever.\nThe name of the postoffice is State\nCollege and the school and its envi-\nrons make up the entire town. It is\none of the greatest of the state col\nleges in the country. The handicap of\nhaving no town at all to support it\nproved to be no handicap at all.\nIt is quite plain that Sioux Falls\nand Huron are not thinking so much\nof the great advantages which they\nwould give to the university and State\ncollege as they are of the great bene\nfits which those schools would give J\nto them. There are colleges located\nat both Sioux Falls and Huron at\nthe present time yet we hear nothing\nof the phenomenal growth they enjoy\nbecause of the splendid advantages\nthey have by being located in those\ncities. State college and the univer\nsity, both have enjoyed a great growth\nIn the last few years. The buildings\nare outgrown as fast as they are\nbuilt. More instructors are needed\nto handle the greatly increased num\nber of students. As rapidly as the\nstate provides facilities for a larger\nnumber of students, the students\ncome. There is no question that if\nState college had buildings, equip\nment and Instructors sufficient for\n2,000 students, there would be 2,000\nstudents enrolled at the present time.\nThe state educational Institutions\nof this state do not need greater sup\nport from the towns, but they do need\ngreater support from the state, it\nIs time South Dakotans discontinued\nthe idea that the state educational in\nstitutions are town institutions. It is\nState college not Brookings college,\nIt is Northern Normal not Aberdeen\nP Normal. It is the University of South\nDakota, not Vermillion university.\nf -w. 8.\nSALESMANSHIP AND SERVICE\nI\nThere is not going to be hard times\nin 1921. Even now the times are not\nhard; they only appear so to some\nI people in contrast to the extrava\ngance and inflation of the previous\nI\nthree or lour years. They have for\ngotten the good old days of twenty\nlive year ago when interest rates\nwer> twenty-two per cent here in\nBrookings and wheat was selling for\n39 cents. But times in 1921 will be\ndifferent than last year Things will\nbe getting back to normal. Pcopte\nwho have things to sell, will have put\nforth a certain amount of effort in\n1921, and not simply throw them at\nthe buyer. 'Die almost, forgotten\nusages of salesmanship and service\nwill come back into vogue for ho.-e\nwho would be successful in business.\nAd' *\u2018i i, in and personal salesmanship\nw ill be ah olute necessith tn 1921\ni Advertising is a service to the buyer\nthat he d< mands. It i the most e o\nnominal des force known ami lor\nthat rej on the merchant who advt r\nt an the buyeis better valm\nslnce his sales costs are lower.\n\u201cWhen we hear of a man cuttin\ndown on his advertising,\" aid a wi-e i\nbank president, \u201cwe cm down on his\ncredit.\" And that is only the begin\nning, Wo all know what the public\ndoes to the man who stops in his ap I\npeal to the peopb at large. It begins\nto forget him. The public seems to\nfeel that something has gone out of\nthe thing or person advertised and\nthey begin to shun it or him con\nsciously or unconsciously.\nFrom every standpoint the present\nis the very best time to buy. Nothing\ni can bring normal conditions and a\nquick return of prosperity and stability\nin every line than a buying campaign\nthat includes everyone. Prices ate\nlower at present than costs would war- I\nrant. In buying now the consumer\nis getting a double benefit. He is\ngetting his goods cheaper than if he\nwaited a couple of months and he is\nimproving appreciably the business\nand economic conditions of his com\nmunity which will help him as much\nas anything else he could do.\n4>W. s. s.\u00ab\nAn exceptionally ingenious method\nof spending the state's money is pro\nvided for in a bill before the legisla\nture providing a bounty of ten cents\nfor every crow and gopher killed. The\nsupply of crows and gophers is un\nlimited. The number of crows that\ncould fly over from neighboring states\nin a day would deplete the treasury if\nall were killed. If the purpose of the\nbill is to provide spending money in\nlarge quantities to crow hunters and\ngopher drenchers, it is admirable. If\ni it is intended to rid the state of\ngophers and crows it is is ridiculous\nuntil such time as the state has its\nboundaries entirely screened in.\n\u2666w. s. s.<?>\nThere appears to be a joker in the\nreparations agreement made by the j\nAllies with Germany. The kick back i\nis in the ad valorem tax of 12*\u00a3 per\ncent on all German products exported.\nIt is evident that the buyers of these\nproducts must pay that additional\ntax. The Allies themselves will be\nthe principal customers and would\ntherefore be paying off Germany's war\ndebts. Not only would the tax come\nout of our pockets but it places a pro\ntective tariff on German Industries at\nthe expense of our own.\n-w. s. s.<\u00ab\nGen. Charles G. Dawes of the United\nStates army got a big round of ap\nplause from over the country for his\nIndelicate, unmincing and generously\nprofane speech to the war investigat\ning committee of congress. The gen\neral hotly resented the effort of the\ncommittee to put a blotch on the army\nfor government waste. \u201cWhat the hell\ndid we go in for,\u2019\u2019 shouts this fiery\nold soldier, \u201cto steal money?\u201d\nTHE MOVIE CENSORSHIP\nPierre Capital-Journal The mem\nbers of the legislature are being\nflooded with letters from people back\nhome asking them to vote for cen\nsorship of moving pictures. Investi\ngation would show- that practically all\nthese letters came from people who\ndo not attend moving picture theatres\nat all or at least very seldom. This\nmatter of censorship of pictures is\nan interference with business where\nthe benefits desired cannot be attained\nby legislation. If the legislature\nof. this state wants to do anything to\nhelp make cleaner pictures the law\nmakers and the people should unite\nIn having one federal review board\nunder authority of the national bu\nreau of education or some other de\npartment. to censor pictures at their\nsource, and then provide that such\npictures could be handled in Inter\nstate commerce without interfernec\nby local authority. The members of\nthe legislature very largely cannot\nunderstand the method which picture\nshow men must follow\u2019 to get service\nthese days. Every exhibitor must put\nup deposits In advance for programs\nmany of which are not even produced\nat the time the deposit made and\neven the titles are not known. These\ndeposits are made under contracts\nwhich are one-sided, but which the\npicture meif must sign in order to get\nTHE BROOKINGS REGISTER, BROOKINGS, S. D., THURSDAY, FEBRUARY 10, 1921.\ns.\nservice. These deposits always ap\nply on the last picture of a contract.\nIn the meantime all pictures are sent\nC. O. D. No matter if the show man\nis worth a million dollars or nothing,\nhe must pay in advance, then if a lo\ncal board objected to the showing of\nthe picture, he would be out his\nI money. So far as state censorship is\nconcerned, it would cost ten dollars\nfor an ordinary show- of five reels, the\naverage show-, for censorship fees.\nThe express item alone in addition,\nwhich the picture men would have to\npay on shipment of a five-reel pro\ngram from Minneapolis or Denver to\n/'ierre, f, am w hich points practically\nall South Dakota films comes, with re\nturn charges would average over three\ndollars a program. It is simply im\npos ible under present conditions from\na financial standpoint alone to stand\nfor this proposed burden on the mov\ning picture industry. The local show\nmen have been forced to raise the r\nprices from live and ten cents to fif\nteen and thirty cents or ven to fifty\ncents already. If any censorship bill\nis passed, either local or state, the\naverage price of admission in South\nDakota would havt to j imp to twenty\nfive ami fifty cents.\nw. s. s.\nFARM PROBLEMS\nSioux City Journal One producer\nwho was hit hard by the shrinkage in\nthe prices of farm products is the\nfarm tenant. Not only did he los<\nthe profits on hi- la.-t year's produe\ntion, but he still has his lease on bi\nhands, by which he is obligated to\npay this year a cash r\u00ab ntal based on\nthe high prices which ruled a year\nago. What is be to do? This is a\nproblem that confronts many tenant\nfarmers.\nAs a result of the slump in prices\nlast year, large numbers of tenant\nfarmers found either that they had\nnot raised enough stuff to pay their\nrent or that it took till they had raised\nto satisfy the landlord\u2019s claim. With\nno certain promise of higher prices,\nwhat are they to do this year? Are\nthey to undertake another season of\nunprofitable labor?\nThe problem is considered by Wai\nlace\u2019s Farmer, which hesitates to ad\nvise any breaking of contracts, but\nsuggests that tenants endeavor to se\ncure from landlords a readjustment\nupon the basis of share rentals. It\nconcedes that the landlord is in posi\ntion to exact his full pound of flesh,\nbut contends that it is neither to his\nadvantage nor to the advantage of\nthe community to do so. There is\nevery reason, Wallace\u2019s Farmer as\nserts, why the land owner should bear\nhis share of the loss occasioned by\nthe drop in prices of farm products.\nThis conclusion is entirely proper\nand right. The loss should be dis\ntributed. The land owner will not be\nadvantaged if tenant farmers shall be\nput out of business, and unquestion\nably many of them will be unable to\nfulfill their contracts based on last\nyear\u2019s prices. It would bp good busi\nness for the landlord to meet the ten\nant half way and consent to a read\njustment that will permit both of them\nto live.\nThe present situation is likely to\ndevelop greater preference for share\nrentals over cash rentals. Many land\nowmers consider that the share rental\nIs the most just and fairest, alike to i\nthe landlord and the renter.\nICE\nPUTTING TEETH IN MOVIES\nSioux City Journal The warning\nissued in Chicago by William A.\nBrady, president of the national asso\nciation of the motion picture indus\ntry, that if attempts at too drastic\ncensorship are continued, the movies\nare likely to be turned into a defen\nsive weapon, might be food for\nthought for some of the blue law ad\nvocates. Although he says he is not\nmaking a declaration of war against\nthe reformers, Mr. Brady points out\nthat the motion picture industry\nreaches 10,000,000 patrons daily. As\na means of propaganda, the effective\nness of this weapon is not to be be\nlittled.\nMotion pictures were devised for\namusement and education. Obviously\nin so big an industry, bad features\ncreep in. Careful determination of\nwhat Aims are objectionable and\nwhat are not, it would seem, would ac\ncomplish vastly more than some of\nthe proposed blanket regulations to\nshut out pictures whose good points\novershadow\u2019 the poorer qualities Some\nof the rules laid down by blue law\nadvocates, Mr. Brady told the Chicago\ncity council, would prevent the show\ning of \"Romeo and Juliet\u201d because of\nthe latter\u2019s suicide; \u201cOthello,\u201d be\ncause a white woman married a ne\ngro, and even the life of Christ l>e\ncause it contains scenes of murder\nand brutality.\nUnfair censorship would threaten\nthe existence of the motion picture\nindustry, and if the producers were\nof a mind tp use their films for de\nfensive propaganda a real fight would\nensue. Such a conflict might kill the\ngood in the reformers\u2019 efforts and at\nthe same time enable the motion pic\nture makers to knock censorship into\na cocked hat. The result would be\nundesirable all around.\nThe flower bill of the country is\nabout >45,000,000. At that it is |5\u00bb-\n000,000 less than the amount spent for\nchewing gum.\n-w. s. s-\n-w. 8. 8.\nHOW TO KILL THE CLUB\nCanova Herald \u2014If you want to kill\nthe business club of your town, Engi\nneering Institute of Canada tells you\nhow to do it. If the coat fits you,\nput it on. Here it is:\nDon't go to the meetings.\n11 you do go, go late.\nIf the weather doesn't suit you, don't\nthink of going.\nIf you attend a meeting, find fault\nwith the work of the officers and mem\nber-.\nNever accept office, as it is easier\nto iticize than do things.\nGet sore if you are not appointed\non committee, but if you are, do not\nattend meetings.\nIf asked by the chairman to give\n>ar epinion on some small matter\nt< 11 him you have nothing to say.\nth< meet ev< ry on< h\nthings should be done.\nDo nothing more than absolutely\nne<e sary, but when members use\nability to help matters along,\nhowl that the institute is run by a\ncI.QUO.\nHold back your dues, or don\u2019t pay\nat ail.\nDon\u2019t bother about getting new mem\nbe \"lx-t George do it.\"\nw. s. s.\n\nUHL RUH NOTES\n\nr 1\u2019: this c >!umn are furnished\nile It -lot'r by the press correspondents\nv irh'U\u00df churches and societies. AU\nch. s .nd societies have tlie same prlvi\ni i tlie use of this column.\nFirst Church of Christ, Scientist\nCornet Sixth street and Fifth avenue.\nServices next Sunday at 11 a. m. Sub\njet t Sunday: \"Soul.\u201d Sunday school\nat 12 o\u2019clock. Wednesday evening\nmeeting at 8:00 o'clock. Reading\nroom in church edifice open every\nWednesday from 2 to 1 p. m. The\nBible and all authorized Christian Sci\nence literature may there be read or\npurchased, if desired. All are cordi\nally invited to attend these services\nand make use of the reading room.\nFirst Presbyterian Church \u2014The ser\nvices at the First Presbyterian church\nnext Sunday will be especially attrac\ntive and the attention of the public is\ninvited to the feature of remarkable\ninterest, the presence of Dr. A. Frank\nHouser of Davenport, la, who will\npre? ch at the evening service at 7:30\no'clock. Dr. Houser is pastor of Cal\nvary church, Davenport, one of the\nstrongest churches of the state and\na speaker of great preaching power.\nDr. Houser will lecture on Monday\nevening at 8:00 o\u2019clock on. \"The Chal\nlenge of the World to Christian Amer\ncia.\u201d This lecture is one of the most\nsuccessful efforts to set forth the op\nportunities and needs of the times,\ndistinguished by constructive insight\nand compelling interest. At the morn\ning service at 10:30 o'clock, the pas\ntor, Rev. James A. G. Waits, will\nMi\nInvestment Quality\nThe\ng\nBank of Brookings\nMiiMMM\nn.,iiwim*.w\nspeak on, \u201cThe Wonder of True\nVision.\u2019\u2019 The Sunday school meets at\nnoon. There are classes for all. The\nsuperintendent, Mr. George W. Ros\nkie, will gladly welcome new mem\nbers and visitors. You will find in\nteresting discussions going on in the\nadult classes and one of the very best\nof orchestras will cheer you up with\ninspiring music. Come! The young\npeople had a splendid social and de\nvotional hour last Sunday. They will\nwelcome you next Sunday evening at\n6:3<\u00bb o\u2019clock.\ni'nited Presbyterian' hurch \u2014Preach-\ning n< xt Sabbath at 10.30 a. m. and\n7:30 p. in. Sabbath school ar 11:45\na. in. Cottage prayer meeting on\nWednesday evening. Before Sabbath,\nFebruary 20, we are to make our of\nlering to the starving men. women,\nand children of China. Our foreign\nboard sends us a heart searching ap\npeal to respond by that day. Some\nhave already made liberal gifts. How\nmany others are ready to do as we\nmight wsh others would do for us\nit we were in similar need,\nBaptist Church \u201cTh* Parable of\nThis Age\u2019 will be the theme of the\nmorning sermon, a discu.-sion of the\n13th chapter of Matthew. Sunday\n00l a 12. and B Y. P. I\u2019, at 6:30.\nAt the oven.ng service the pastor will\npn aeh the tirst of three sermons an\nnounced. the theme being, \u201cThe\nTheater, the Kingdom of God, and\nLife,' oi what is the theater doing\nto people'.\u2019 The otln r subnets which\nwill be especially for young people\nwill be \u201cHow Shall a Man Choo-e\n\u25a0a Wife? which will be given on\nPresbyterian Church\nSubject Morning Service\n\u201cThe Wonder of True Vision\u201d\nEvening Service\nDr. A. Frank Houser of Davenport, lowa Will Preach\nDo not fail to hear the message of this powerful pulpit orator\nAT 7:30 P. M.\nThe Public is Cordially Invited to Attend These Services\nThere is such a thing as quali\nty in the matter of making an\ninvestment.\nCertificates of Deposit offered\nby the only Guaranty Bank in\nBrookings offer an investment\nof highest quality.\nYou can buy a \"C. D.\u201d in any\namount at any time your\nmoney earns at a 5 percent\nrate for six months and 6 per\ncent for twelve months and the\nsafety of this money is guar\nanteed under state law.\nDeal with men you know\u2014be\nware the \"wildcat\u201d speculation.\nWe are here to work with you\nfor mutual good.\nREV. JAMES\nSunday\nFebruary\nSUNDAY SCHOOL AT NOON\nWITH ORCHESTRA\nCLASSES FOR ALL\nYoung People\u2019s Meeting at 6:30 P. M.\nFebruary 20, and \u201cHow Shall a\nWoman Choose a Husband?\u201d will be\ngiven February 27. The social for the\nvocational boys of the college given\nby the church last Friday evening was\na great success. A large number of\nthem and their wives were present\nand with singing, games, refreshments\nand getting acquainted the evening\nslipped by quickly.\nLutheran Church\u2014Dr. G. M. Bruce\nof St. Paul. Minn., will speak at the\nevening services, subject: \u201cChurch\nand Its Confessions.\u201d In the morning\nthe Rt. Rev. N. N. Boe of Sioux Falls,\nwill give an address in the Norwegian\nlanguage. Last Sunday afternoon the\ncollege bible class entertained the\nhigh school and Aggie classes at the\nchurch. After a most enjoyable after\nnoon a line lunch was served.\nw. s. s.\nWhen he grasped a wire to save\nhimself from plunging into the half\nfrozen and icy Big Sioux river. 14-year\nold Harvey Crom was electrocuted in\nDel) Rapids last Thursday afternoon.\nH\u2019- was climbing the overhead struc\nture of the west bridge over the Sioux\nriver, and wa- about 40 to 50 feet in\nthe air when he lost his grip and fell\ntoward the water. In the descent his\noutstretched arms caught the electric\nwire and its high voltage proved fatal.\nw. s s.\nPruning of orchard trees may be\ndone on warm days now.\nKeep aphis off house plants by dip\nping them in water to which some\nnicotine solution has been added. Then\nclean the plants by washing them with\nclean water.\nFirst\nA. G. WAITS,\n13 th\n10:30 O\u2019clock\nMinister","height":"35716","width":"25888"}}
